POLIO - CHINA: BACKGROUND
************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
[see: Polio - China (Qinghai): alert 20000107063416]
Date: Fri, 07 Jan 2000 17:35:11 +0200
From: "Stephen A. Berger, M.D." <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

The following background data on poliomyelitis in China were extracted from
the
GIDEON software program http://www.cyinfo.com/ :
Infant vaccine coverage was 98% as of 1990. Routine immunization (OPV) is
administered at ages 3, 4 and 5 months; and 4 years.
Children under age 3 have accounted for 83% of cases (for an age-specific
rate
of 4.3/100 000); and most cases have been due to type 1. Hong Kong's last
case
of wild viral infection was reported in 1983.
Year Cases reported
1978 110 408
1979 5472
1981 9625
1987 969
1988 667
1989 4628
1990 5065
1991 2009
1992 1372
1993 265
1994 261
1995 189
1996 3
1997 0
1998 0
4372 cases of Acute Flaccid Paralysis [AFP] were reported in 1996;
3977 in 1997;
4638 in 1998.
--
Steve Berger
Department of Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[AFP is paralysis clinically similar to polio but due to different viruses -
Mod.JW]
